RT @DeborahSuggRyan: @Scandiwegians Unbelievably, Robert Welch never won the Duke of Edinburgh’s Award for Elegant Design. The Campden toas…

Before creating it, Robert filled nearly a whole sketchbook with ideas. He could really let his imagination run with designs for trophies and he described this one as 'tiddlywinks in the abstract' https://t.co/QsJhqxu68b

It was engraved with the Royal Coat of Arms on one side and ‘The Silver Wink’ on the other, it is free to spin but weighted so that it always comes to rest with the royal coat of arms facing forward. The trophy stands on a rosewood base and is 15½" high https://t.co/5bPSBhoxJf

Known as the 'Silver Wink', it was for presentation to the winner of the annual Inter-University Tiddlywink Championship, a match held between Oxford and Cambridge Universities’ Tiddlywink Societies, of which the DofE was President https://t.co/gg1NyQGH9J
But by far my favourite was this trophy commissioned by Prince Philip https://t.co/ZxBnmto49a
You can see them on the table behind the Duke in this @BritishPathe film: https://t.co/chLbbnLOjq

Robert was later commissioned to design two silver presentation candlesticks for the Duke of Edinburgh to give as a prize for elegant design at the Design Centre Awards 1961. These went to Neal French (Ceramic Designer) and David White, and were only he second ever presented. https://t.co/Ya2r9CUZXt

One of my favourite photos in the @robertwelchuk  archive is of a young Robert Welch talking to the Duke of Edinburgh in 1957.
